  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 7.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Send me...  a man cunning to work",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. The parenthesis is now ended. By comparison of ver. 3, it appears that Solomon makes of Hiram's services to David his father a very plea why his own requests addressed now to Hiram should be granted. If we may be guided by the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "form",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the expressions used in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 14:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 5:11, 12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Hiram had in the first instance volunteered help to David, and had not waited to be applied to by David. This would show us more clearly the force of Solomon's plea. Further, if we note the language of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 5:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", we may be disposed to think that it fills a gap in our present connection, and indicates that, though Solomon appears here to have had to take the initiative, an easy opportunity was opened, in the courteous embassy sent him in the persons of Hiram's \"servants.\" That the king of this most privileged, separate, and exclusive people of Israel (and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "he",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the one who conducted that people to the very zenith of their fame) should have to apply and be permitted to apply to foreign and, so to say, heathen help, in so intrinsic a matter as the finding of the \"cunning\" and the \"skill\" of head and hand for the most sacred and distinctive ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "chef d'oeuvre",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the said exclusive nation, is a grand instance of nature breaking all trammels, even when most divinely purposed, and a grand token of the dawning comity of nations, of free-trade under the unlikeliest auspices, and of the brotherhood of humanity, never more broadly illustrated than when on an international scale. The competence of the Phoenicians and the people of Sidon and those over whom Hiram immediately reigned in the working of the metals, and furthermore in a very wide range of other subjects, is well sustained by the allusions of very various authorities (already instanced under 1 Chronicles 14:1, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "passim",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Homer, 'Iliad,' 6:289-294; 23. 743; 'Odys.,' 4:614; 15:415-426; Herod., 3:19; 7:23, 44, 96; Strabo, 16:2. § 23). The man who was sent is described in vers. 13, 14, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "infra",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as also ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 7:13, 14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Purple, ... crimson, ... blue",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It is not absolutely necessary to suppose that the same Hiram, so skilled in working of gold, silver, brass, and iron, was ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " authority sent for these matters of various coloured dyes for the cloths that would later on be required for curtains and other similar purposes in the temple. So far, indeed, as the literal construction of the words go, this would seem to be what is meant, and no doubt ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "may",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " have been the case, though unlikely. The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "purple",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "אַדְגְּוָן",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). A Chaldee form of this word (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "אַרְגְּוָנָא",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") occurs three times in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 5:7, 16, 29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and appears in each of those cases in our Authorized Version as \"scarlet.\" Neither of these words is the word used in the numerous passages of Exodus, Numbers, Judges, Esther, Proverbs, Canticles, Jeremiah, and Ezekiel, nor, indeed, in ver. 13, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "infra",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 3:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In all these places, numbering nearly forty, the word is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "אַרְגָבָן",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The purple was probably obtained from some shell-fish on the coast of the Mediterranean. The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "crimson",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "כַרְמִיל",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Gesenius says that this was a colour obtained from multitudinous insects that tenanted one kind of the flex (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Coccus ilicis",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and that the word is from the Persian language. The Persian ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "kerm",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Sanscrit ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "krimi",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Armenian ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "karmir",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", German ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "carmesin",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and our own \"crimson,\" keep the same framework of letters or sound to a remarkable degree. This word is found only here, ver. 13, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "infra",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 3:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "crimson",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 1:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 4:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "scarlet",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of some forty places in the Pentateuch and other books, come as the rendering of the word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "שָׁנִי",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "blue",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "תְּכֵלֶת",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). This is the same word as is used in some fifty other passages in Exodus, Numbers, and in later books. This colour was obtained from a shell-fish (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Helix ianthina",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") found in the Mediterranean, the shell of which was blue. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Can skill to grave",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The word \"to grave\" is the piel conjugation of the very familiar Hebrew verb ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "פָּתַח",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"to open.\" Out of twenty-nine times that the verb occurs in some part of the piel conjugation, it is translated \"grave\" nine times, \"loosed\" eleven times, \"put off\" twice, \"ungirded\" once, \"opened\" four times, \"appear\" once, and \"go free\" once. Perhaps the \"opening\" the ground with the plough (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 28:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") leads most easily on to the idea of \"engraving.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Cunning men whom... David...  did",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " provide, As we read in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 22:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 28:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". 2 Chronicles 2:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The materials Hiram was to send were cedar, cypress, and algummim wood from Lebanon. אלגוּמים, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 2:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 9:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", instead of אלמגּים,   ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 10:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", probably means sandal wood, which was employed in the temple, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 10:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", for stairs and musical instruments, and is therefore mentioned here, although it did not grow in Lebanon, but, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 9:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 10:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", was procured at Ophir. Here, in our enumeration, it is inexactly grouped along with the cedars and cypresses brought from Lebanon.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]